title: For Sale/Trade:  VTAC 9mm, Shield 9mm & M9A1 for 1911
postcontent:
I have three 9mm pistols to trade for a 1911 with rail. First off is a Smith and Wesson M&P 9mm VTAC edition with Warrior 6 dot day/night sights. The frame and slide are both FDE.  Comes will box, papers, 2 17 round mags, and a Raven Concealment Phantom Holster. The gun was made in 2014 and has no wear to the PVD finish on the slide.  The top of the barrel where the pistol locks up is starting to get some shine (actually had a little wear from the factory if you can believe that).  Its seen 100-150 rounds not exactly sure on count.

Next up is a Smith and Wesson M&P 9mm shield.  The gun is only about a month old with about 20 rounds through it.  Sweet shooter especially considering the size of the pistol.  It comes with box, papers, one 7 round and one 8 round magazine as well as a 
Galco Ankle Lite holster, and two custom kydex holsters made by a friend of mine.  The Shield shows some wear on the slide from being carried.  I was very disappointed at how weak the finish was on the high points of the slide but it does not seem to be wearing anywhere else.  This gun is a fantastic carry piece and is perfect for summer carry. 

Last but not least is the Beretta M9A1.  This gun is the beast with the rail built into the frame.  If you have ever wanted a beretta, this is the one to get in my opinion.  I was going to keep the gun in a glass case but decided Id rather have something to shoot.  It is in flawless unfired condition. Ive had it since April 2nd and I am the only owner.  It comes with two PVD coated 15 round mags from the factory as well as an 18 round mec-gar mag.  The M9A1 has much improved grip serrations, a beveled magazine well, and 3-dot sights over the standard service M9.

I am looking to trade 2-3 of these for a 1911 with rail.  I am looking for a Springfield TRP Operator (will trade all 3 for) Springfield MC operator, Springfield LW operator , Colt Rail Gun, Kimber Warrior, 1911 tradidional tac ops from sig sauer.

If intersted in buying any of these guns individually, text or email me for price.  I know this is a long ad, thanks for reading. REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Browning BDM
postcontent:
14-9030 The Browning BDM is a semi-automatic pistol designed and manufactured by the Browning Arms Company up until production ceased in 1998. Similar in appearance to Browning's (FN Herstal) P-35 model "Hi-Power" pistol, the BDM was actually a new design created to compete in service trials as a standard issue pistol for the United States Federal Bureau of Investigation. However, the BDM was not ultimately adopted for issue by the FBI, and was instead sold only in the private market.

The Browning BDM was developed in 1991 by the Browning Arms Company, and unlike Browning's (FN Herstal) P-35 Hi-Power model, was manufactured only in North America.

The pistol is a magazine fed, self-loading, hammer firing type which was designed with a trigger "mode" switch installed on the left-hand side of the slide (actually only a flush inlaid disk with a bisecting groove), toggling between double-action/single-action(DA/SA) pistol mode, and the double-action-only (DAO) or "revolver" mode—though, of course, other than the similarity of the trigger mode, the BDM has no resemblance to revolvers. This mode switch is what gives the handgun its name, with BDM standing for "Browning Dual Mode" or "Browning Double Mode".

Variants of the design lacked the mode operating switch, and so were either full-time revolver mode, model BRM (Browning Revolver Mode), or full-time double action/single action pistol mode, model BPM-D (Browning Pistol Mode Decocker). Finishes included blued, matte-chromed, which Browning advertising called "silver chrome", and a two-toned combination of a silver chromed frame and blued slide, called the "practical" finish.

The BDM and BPM-D variants have an ambidextrous slide-mounted safety/decocker lever, which when operated always returns the pistol to the hammer down double-action setting for the BDM variant or to the pre-cocked setting for the BPM-D variant. After the next fired cartridge cycles the pistol's slide, subsequent rounds are fired in the single-action mode, until the decocker is used to drop the hammer to the "safe" position. The BPM-D innovation was the inclusion into the action of the pre-cocked mode in which the hammer is partially cocked and the hammer spring partially depressed resulting in a first shot trigger pull that is shorter and lighter than in the true DA variants. The BRM variant lacks a safety/decocker lever, leaving the pistol in the hammer down "safe" double-action position after every shot, i.e. DAO.

The BDM and its variants utilize removable cartridge magazines, of the double stack variety with a capacity of 15 rounds of 9x19mm Parabellum ammunition. To comply with the 1994 U.S. Assault Weapons legislation, BDM magazines were limited to 10 round capacity for civilian purchasers, although 15 round magazines were available for law enforcement use. After the 2004 expiration of the 1994 U.S. Assault Weapons legislation, 15 round magazines became legal and available in most states for civilian use.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1892 32WCF
postcontent:
14-9031 This one is a 1909 Manufacture!!

The Winchester Model 1892 was a lever-action repeating rifle designed by John Browning as a smaller, lighter version of his large-frame Model 1886, and which replaced the Model 1873 as the company's lever-action for pistol-caliber rounds such as the .44-40.

When asked by Winchester to design an improved pistol caliber lever action, John Browning said he would have the prototype completed in under a month or it would be free. Within 2 weeks, Browning had a functioning prototype of the 92.[2] Calibers for the rifle vary and some are custom-chambered. The original rounds were the .32-20, .38-40, and .44-40 Winchester centerfire rounds, followed in 1895 by the new .25-20.[3] A few Model 92's chambered for .218 Bee were produced in 1936-38.[3]

The Winchester Models 53 (1924) and 65 (1933) were relabeled Model 1892's. Admiral Robert E. Peary carried an 1892 on his trips to the North Pole.,[3] and Secretary of War Patrick Hurley was presented with the one millionth rifle on December 13, 1932.

1,007,608 Model 1892 rifles were made by Winchester, and although the company phased them out by 1945, they are still being made under the Puma label by the Brazilian arms maker, Rossi, by Chiappa Firearms, an Italian factory, and by Browning in Japan. In its modern form, using updated materials and production techniques, the Model 1892's action is strong enough to chamber high pressure handgun rounds, such as .357 Magnum, .44 Magnum, and .454 Casull. Despite being designed for smaller cartridges, the 1892's dual forward locking-block action is actually stronger than Browning's rear-locked Model 1894.[4]

Although the Model 1892 made its debut after the closing of the American frontier, and the true "Guns that Won the West" were the earlier Models 1866 and 1873, nonetheless the '92 became an indelible icon of Western mythology through its use in hundreds of motion pictures and television shows, standing in for its older siblings. John Wayne famously carried Model 92s in dozens of films and owned several personally, some with the distinctive oversized "loop" lever. Other notable screen 92s were those of Chuck Connors in The Rifleman TV series, and Steve McQueen's "Mare's Leg" in Wanted: Dead or Alive.[5]

Hollywood studios purchased the '92 in quantity because it was in regular production (until World War II) but looked sufficiently like Old West Winchesters to substitute for valuable antiques, and because in calibers .44-40 and .38-40 it could fire, together with the Colt Single Action Army "Peacemaker" revolver, the standard Five-in-One blank cartridge. This latter practice mirrored the real cowboys, who found it convenient to carry a rifle and a revolver chambered with the same ammunition.

title: For Sale:  1983 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme ONLY 26K miles mint interior
location: Roxbury NJ, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
1983 Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme with only 26,800 miles with a 3.8 liter V6 and an automatic transmission. This car was owned by one family (2 owners were sisters) and is in amazing shape. The exterior is a light brown while the interior is brown. This car has several features including power windows, door locks, cruise control, rear defroster, air conditioning, and a factory cassette stereo system. 

 The interior is in amazing condition as it does not have any rips, tears, or stains. The arm rest is in good working condition as well as the seat belts do not show signs of wear. Many people including myself feel these cars have extremely comfortable seats. The car was never smoked in and the three ashtrays (two of the ashtrays are behind the driver & passenger seat) and cigarette lighter are clean, not showing signs of use. 

 The car has the original floor mats for all four seating areas and they are also in great shape (free of stains, tears, or rips.) The trunk area is extremely clean, not showing any rust while the factory black carpet looks is in mint condition. The spare tire and jack are also free of rust, properly mounted, and do not look like they have ever been used. The original diagrams are attached to the trunk lid on spare tire usage (one is taped on.) 

 The car has new white wall tires and mechanically has always been maintained. Currently the fluids look clean while the air filter looks brand new. The car has also passed New Jersey vigorous emissions standards and has a valid inspection sticker.

 Like all vehicles with age this car shows signs of exterior wear and I will list whatever defects I noticed here. The trunk has some rusty scratches on it. The driver's rear corner looks as if someone backed into something. The front corner roof on the driver's side has a rusty one inch scratch with a small indentation. The vinyl covering on the roof has tears while the trim that goes toward the front of the car is faded. The middle to lower panel on the driver's driver has a large indentation on it. As most of the wear on this car is external, please see the pictures to determine the exact condition.
 Mechanically the car starts up and all of the options are in working condition. The power stereo antenna struggles to go up thus the owner's mechanic unplugged it leaving it fully extended. The air conditioning does not get cool when it is activated and probably needs to be charged. The car sounds like it could have an exhaust leak and at times a check engine light comes on at times. I believe it is possible that the exhaust system is triggering this however it is not hindering the vehicle running at all. The exhaust system does looks like it's in great condition as it does not show any rot. Two of the wheels are missing the center caps covers. The vehicle does include the factory anti-theft tool to remove the wheels. 

 This is a great opportunity to own a one family female owned, factory original Oldsmobile with only 26,800 miles on it.

title: For Sale:  WWII USGI 1911A1 Parts
postcontent:
For sale is the last of my WWII USGI 1911A1 parts.  These were the 'best of the best' that I was keeping for myself, but my interests have changed.

I know everybody thinks their crap is stuff, and your stuff is crap, but I'll tell you this:  These parts are invaluable if you deal in WWII GI .45s.  It is very common to find an otherwise correct GI 1911A1, that somebody has swapped small parts out on - especially mainspring housings, triggers, and hammers.

As such, these parts have become very sought-after and pricey, as they are necessary to make these expensive collectible guns correct.  Do an advanced search on eBay, and check the box for "completed listings", and see what these things are selling for.  

For just one example, a coarse checkered Colt MSH like one that I have here just sold on 5/5 for $195, with NO internals and NO lanyard loop.  Mine has all internals and lanyard loop - and that's just one part.

So, here's what I have:

- Six (6) mainspring housings (two checkered; two 8-rib serrated; two 7-rib serrated.  The finer checkered MSH has the plunger pin but no internals.  One each of the 7-rib and 8-rib MSH has no internals)
- Three (3) short wide-spur hammers (two borderless; one bordered)
- Two (2) stamped triggers (one has what appears to be a Du-Lite blue on it for a US&S)
- Three (3) long tang grip safeties (one has nice worn look; one looks like it's been blued; and one looks like NOS and is "x" marked)

I calculated a conservative total value of these parts, based on average ACTUAL SOLD eBay prices - not even using the $195 example.  There is easily over $1000 worth of parts here - I'm not counting the blued grip safety in that number, as - while GI - blued is not right.  

My 'pre-negotiated' price is $450 firm.  The MSHs alone are worth way more than that.  I will only sell them as a lot, so please don't ask for individual prices, or "how much for just the hammers", etc.  I'm sorry if that sounds curt, but if I had the time to sell them individually, I'd list them on eBay and make a heap more $$$.  

I would consider a trade for certain WWII collectibles - particularly helmets.  Let me know what you have, the worst I can say is "no thank you".  

Please let me know if you have any questions.  Thank you.
